Checking for missing values¶

It is important to first verify that there are no missing value in the data. In this next cell I use a function _missingcheck to process the data frame and check for missing values.

In [107]:
def missing_check(df):
    total = df.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending = False)
    percent = (df.isnull().sum() / df.isnull().count()).sort_values(ascending = False)
    missing_data = pd.concat([total, percent], axis = 1, keys = ['Total', 'Percent'])
    return missing_data
missing_check(cardio_good_fitness)

Customer Profile¶

  • Age: 18 - 50 with an average age of 29
  • Customers use the product between 2 and 7 days a week with an average of 3 or 4 days a week
  • Customers in the sample set were 58% male and 42% female
  • 59% of customers are partnered, leaving 41% single
  • On the average, customers experienced higher usage and milage, and had reported higher levels of fitness with the TM798 product
  • Customers with a higher income level tended to use the TM798 over the other products available
  • The sample data contained 44% tm195 users, 33% tm498 users, 22% tm798 users

Insights and Recommendations for Targeting New Customers¶

  • The most revenue is likely achieved by targeting partnered males in their thirties with higher income levels
  • The TM798 is the best product to focus on, as customers are using it more frequently and getting better overal results
  • Only 22% of customers are currently using the TM798 rather than other models
